DURBAN - South Africa’s national police commissioner Khehla Sitole yesterday condemned the attack on officers who responded to business robberies at two filling stations in Nongoma, KwaZulu-Natal on Monday morning.
Police spokesperson Brenda Muridili said members of Nongoma visible policing were ambushed while responding to the calls.

“On arrival they were met by a hail of bullets, and retaliated. Suspects fled the scene and three police officers were taken to hospital,” said Muridili.
General Sitole commended the members for their bravery. “Our members are fearless and this incident bears witness that we, as the police will not be deterred. We will continue our endeavours to ensure citizens are and feel safe. We will always put our lives on the line in pursuit of our Constitutional mandate.
“I have directed the provincial management to ensure all the members who responded to these business robberies be supported and afforded a debriefing by our Employee Health and Wellness.”

Chairperson of the portfolio committee on police Francois Beukman also condemned the attack and said the committee favoured the deployment of specialised units in hotspots.
Police urged anyone with information to contact their nearest police station or call Crime Stop on 08600 10111, callers will remain anonymous. 
- African News Agency (ANA)